You need to compile from source to get CoreML support, I think the selector on onnxruntime.ai is misleading here by saying it's compiled in the binary on Maven Central (@faxu should that be updated?).

Cmake pulls in the JNI support by looking for the `$JAVA_HOME` environment variable and reading things out of that. The default location for OpenJDK in Homebrew is `/opt/homebrew/opt/openjdk/`, so try setting it to that.

Running `./build.sh --update --build --build_java --config Release --parallel --use_coreml` on an M1 laptop with macOS 13.4 on a clean checkout of `v1.15.0` still gives me an error when adding CoreML and it looks like it's because the name of the native flag changed. If you modify line 603 of [this file](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/java/src/main/native/ai_onnxruntime_OrtSession_SessionOptions.c#L603) to say `#ifdef USE_COREML`, note there is only one underscore, then you should get a CoreML compatible jar file. I'll put in a PR with the fix.

Thanks so much for the detailed response, seems like `JAVA_HOME` and `cmake` are acting naughty on my machine. 
if I do `ls $JAVA_HOME/include` I see 
```
classfile_constants.h jawt.h                jawt_md.h             jdwpTransport.h       jni.h                 jni_md.h              jvmti.h               jvmticmlr.h
```

but when I run `./build.sh --update --build --build_java --config Release --parallel --use_coreml` I still get this error- 

```
CMake Error at /Applications/CMake.app/Contents/share/cmake-3.26/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:230 (message):
  Could NOT find JNI (missing: JAVA_INCLUDE_PATH JAVA_INCLUDE_PATH2 AWT)
Call Stack (most recent call first):
  /Applications/CMake.app/Contents/share/cmake-3.26/Modules/FindPackageHandleStandardArgs.cmake:600 (_FPHSA_FAILURE_MESSAGE)
  /Applications/CMake.app/Contents/share/cmake-3.26/Modules/FindJNI.cmake:569 (find_package_handle_standard_args)
  onnxruntime_java.cmake:16 (find_package)
  CMakeLists.txt:1631 (include)
```
so it seems like `JAVA_HOME` is not being honored by `cmake` or it is somehow not able to read it. There is some reference to the problem [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53876767/cmake-not-finding-jni-when-java-home-is-set-correctly). 

If you don't mind, @Craigacp , can you please share what is the output of  ` ls $JAVA_HOME` on your machine? 


Also, note that I was suspecting something wrong with `cmake` installed through `brew` so I installed the binary from cmake official site, that's why you see `/Applications/CMake.app/Contents/share/cmake` in the error log I posted. 


On a different note, are there plans of shipping CoreML JNI binary through Maven packages? Given there are already binaries available in the jar file, I think it will be a good idea - a lot of people will be running into build issues otherwise.

Ahh. It seems like homebrew packages OpenJDK oddly, so `/opt/homebrew/opt/openjdk` isn't quite the right place. For homebrew JDKs I have `/opt/homebrew/opt/openjdk/libexec/openjdk.jdk/Contents/Home` which looks like it's got the right things in it. The CMake detection wants to find the libraries to make sure it's got it, and the other folder doesn't have a `lib`.

I don't know if there are plans to include CoreML in the Maven package, the binary is already pretty large and it would complicate the packaging (as I think you'd need to build on a specific version of macOS). That's a question for the ORT developers though, I just maintain the Java API, I'm not responsible for it's packaging.

You should make sure you've run a build with `--update` as adding the CoreML flag on it's own might change the build options. You also need to add the `--build` flag, I don't know if it's automatically implied by the other ones.

I'm using the latest XCode on my M1 along with macOS 13.4, that might be important, I know there were changes to CoreML in the past few months and it didn't build correctly for me when I tried it in March.

ORT doesn't build on Xcode 14.3 now without some modifications. Here's a workaround for that particular issue:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/15878/files#diff-cf577ff910eb6272a6a671d1c3eeb1b3b5a6d24357332306e37f8ea533b8cf2d

#15878 should get things building again.

Thank you, @edgchen1  and @Craigacp; I was able to build the library and load an onnx model successfully after applying the changes that both of you have published. 

FWIW, if anyone else is blocked, here are the steps- 

1. checkout @edgchen1 's branch https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/15878 and then apply @Craigacp branch https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/16231

2. build using - 
```
./build.sh --config Release --build_java  --skip_submodule_sync --parallel --skip_tests --cmake_extra_defines CMAKE_OSX_ARCHITECTURES=arm64 --use_coreml
```
3. Done! You should have `./build/MacOS/Release/java/build/libs/onnxruntime-1.16.0.jar` 

Note that I am purposefully skipping tests here due to test failures, @edgchen1 - FYI.

On a clean checkout of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/15878 with my changes in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/16231, built using `./build.sh --update --config Debug --build --build_java --parallel` on a 2020 M1 13" MBP, macOS 13.4 with XCode 14.2 I get the attached stack trace log out of the JVM when it goes bang. It was running this test in Java - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/java/src/test/java/ai/onnxruntime/InferenceTest.java#L383 which I think was the first test to properly hit MLAS.

It's dying with SIGILL (which means it hit an illegal instruction), so maybe it hit an unexpected SIMD instruction from another ARM chip? I usually see SIGILL when Rosetta hits an Intel AVX instruction, but this is an ARM64 binary so I don't know what's going on.

[hs_err_pid38482.log](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/11671764/hs_err_pid38482.log)
